  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      To find out the safety and efficacy of Optical Coherence Tomography (OCT) in the evaluation
      and treatment of angiographically borderline coronary artery lesions in a Chinese population,
      and to compare the effectiveness of OCT versus SPECT in treating such subjects. All the
      participants included in the study will be those that are found to have borderline coronary
      artery lesions on coronary angiography, in whom the investigators feel that OCT will be
      useful to assess whether PCI will be of benefit to the treatment of the lesion pathology, or
      whether optimal medical therapy is the most appropriate treatment modality. Those
      participants who declined OCT will be offered SPECT as an alternative method to assess and
      treat the borderline coronary artery stenosis.

      It is estimated that OCT guided &quot;PCI or not&quot; has a non-inferiority to SPECT's in the
      borderline coronary artery stenosis.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
